Transport Minister Fikile Mbalula says staff are working overtime to address the driver's licence backlog, which runs into the hundreds of thousands. The minister and Road Traffic Management Corporation officials are providing an update. JOHANNESBURG - It will take at least four months to clear the current driver's license backlog. That’s according to Transport Minister Fikile Mbalula. Mbalula was referring to the cards which are currently on the system. READ: Insurance companies exercise leniency over driver’s licence backlog "Considering that the current backlog of 597,000 awaiting to be printed, we anticipate that it will take approximately four months to clear the backlog," he said. "We have conducted an assessment of the quantum of the backlog and evaluated challenges faced by motorists in renewing licenses. READ: AA: Rip out and replace licence system "We have also considered factors like further extension as well as law enforcement capacity to ensure the rule of law prevails," Mbalula said. "The total backlog of licenses that would have expired by 31 March stands at 2.1 million nationwide, of this number those that fall in Covid-19 extension account for 70 percent, that is 1.5 million people." A new card in October 2023 will be introduced. Once we start issuing the new card, we will phase out the current card over a 5-year period, which should allow the current cards to expire. pic.twitter.com/rtH1UBBZUS As of 1st February 2022; there is production backlog of 597k driving license cards. #DLTCs pic.twitter.com/qy9fIcFrm0